If I apply to School_A first, I lose to Student_A in Step 2 (since A will be rejected from B and then apply to A), so School_A is unattainable. If instead I apply to School_C in Step 1, I beat Student_C (who applies to C) because I have higher priority than C, so I secure School_C permanently—my best achievable outcome. After that, the remaining order should follow my true preferences among still-possible options: School_A (unlikely), then School_E, then School_D; School_B is placed last since it will be filled by Student_A in Step 1.
